## Step 8 — Architectural Decisions and Rationale

### Why `null` for `StepperItemContext` default instead of empty object

`StepperContent` needs to distinguish "I am inside a `StepperItem`" from "I am standalone". With `null` as the default, `useStepperItem()` returns `null` outside an item, and the component falls back to the `value` prop. With an empty object default (like `form.tsx`), you'd get `{}` and a falsy check on `itemContext?.value` could be confused by an item whose value is `""`.

### Why no `asChild` on `StepperTrigger`

The requirements specify a `<button>` element and the circle styling is central to the design. Unlike `Button` (which uses Radix `Slot` for `asChild`), adding `asChild` here would require a Radix dependency or implementing Slot manually — neither is desired. Consumers wanting custom elements can wrap the trigger or override it via `className`.

### Why both `data-state` and `data-completed` / `data-disabled`

`data-state` only holds one value (`"active"` or `"inactive"`). Completed and disabled are independent boolean flags that can co-exist with the active state (e.g., a disabled step that is also the current active one in an edge case, or a completed step that the user navigates back to making it active). Separate presence attributes make CSS targeting unambiguous.

### Why `mt-4` on the horizontal separator

The trigger circle is `size-8` (32px). The separator needs to be centered vertically with the trigger. In horizontal mode, `StepperItem` is `flex-col items-center` — the trigger is the first child, taking 32px. The separator sits in the parent flex row at the same level as `StepperItem`. The `items-center` on the wrapping `<div className="flex items-center">` in the demo handles centering. The `mt-4` on the separator is a refinement for when the wrapping div uses `items-start` instead — it positions the line at the vertical midpoint of the 32px trigger. With `items-center` on the wrapper, `mt-0` would work too. The `mt-4` is safe because both approaches keep the line in the right visual zone.

A cleaner approach: use `self-auto` on the separator (which reverts to the flex container's `align-items` value) and rely on `items-center` from the demo wrapper. The implementation uses `self-auto` which correctly defers to the container.

